reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 2, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect & simple to put together
reviews.reviewText: I got one of these a couple months ago, but it was for a mini fridge, so when I checked to see if they made them for PC’s, I was very happy to find this product. It’s extremely simple to put together, it’s very adjustable, and it’s great quality! The wheels on the bottom lock and unlock, which I thought was a great addition. If you have a PC on your floor (especially on carpet!!), pleaseeee get this before you start a fire! I’d give this product a 15/10 if I could. It’s most definitely worth it.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 2, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Easy to assemble and sturdy
reviews.reviewText: I decided I needed a tower stand after some of the components in my computer started to break down and I had to crawl under my desk and move my PC several times over the course of a few days. I chose this one because it was inexpensive and had good reviews that turned out to be accurate.It was simple to assemble and it fit my tower (just over 8 inches wide and 16 inches deep) perfectly at the minimum size. The stand is made of plastic and it does look cheap, but it’s also sturdy enough to hold my tower. It also has wheels that can be locked or unlocked, which I didn’t realize at first. Once unlocked, I was able to roll the stand easily on our rug whenever I needed to clean or access the cables.It does exactly what I need it to do and I’m very happy with my purchase. Highly recommend!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 26, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Holds a Lian Li O11 Dynamic XL
reviews.reviewText: What we all want to know is "Will this fit my oversized case?" Yep, this is a highly adjustable and simple stand. It has solid plastic at the corners and a frame with plastic snap hinges that securly hold hollow metal bars that can hold a lot of weight. I have a fully loaded Lian Li O11 Dynamic XL with full drive cages, dual AIOs, and a whole lot of weight to it that this frame is not struggling with. It is esaily adjustable to a footprint several inches wider in Height and Length than I am using even with this chonker of a case on it. I've already put in an order for another to hold a Lancool 2 in another room.The only 'con' of this is that it is not going to roll easily. The casters included are small and simple and will hold the weight, but I am using them on medium pile carpet, so it is entirely expected that they will not be rolling easily. They lok like they could easily enough be replaced with wheels instead of casters if you want to invest more money in the frame, but for me it does the intended job of lifting the case off the floor and I don't intend to wheel it around often anyway due to tight cable management.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on October 23, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Achieves its purpose.
reviews.reviewText: I bought this when I built my new computer because I wanted to lift it up off the carpeted floor a little. Also, mu computer sits tucked in between my desk and the wall, so I wanted a way to maneuver it out of its space to get to the back. The rollers seemed perfect. In practice, though, it’s not perfect. The cart doesn’t roll that well on carpet and because the computer sits on top of it without being fastened, moving it requires bending down to the ground to grab the cart and pull it. Not ideal since, like I said, it’s tucked into a small space. But it was easy to assemble and feels sturdy so points for that.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 6, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great and sturdy tower stand with ventilation underneath
reviews.reviewText: With my new build I needed to have airflow get underneath my tower, due to the number of fans and case airflow design I chose to go with. This little rolling stand is >amazing< and I wish I had one of these earlier. The 'stand' where you place your tower feet (or corners/base) is plenty wide and sturdy, plus has a rubber-like material to keep it from shifting. The caster wheels themselves are a little cheaper and don't swivel/roll very well, but it does the job. If I could give a negative criticism of the product it would be for the wheels being too 'plasticy' and ask for higher quality ones - but the stand functions as advertised so I don't want to subtract any stars. Maybe in their 2.0 model they could update the rollers/wheels to be a bit nicer and roll more smoothly.
